# GerenciaX Backend — AI Coding Rules
# Stack: NestJS 10+ · TypeScript 5.4+ strict · Supabase (PostgreSQL 16+) · Drizzle ORM
# Architecture: Modular Monolith + Hexagonal Architecture (Ports & Adapters)
# Full docs: docs/00-ai-system-prompt.md (system prompt) + 12 skill files

## CRITICAL RULES — Never Violate

### Hexagonal Architecture
- Domain layer NEVER imports from Infrastructure or Application
- Ports are pure TypeScript interfaces (no NestJS decorators)
- Entities validate their own state in constructor/methods
- Services inject via `@Inject('PortName')` string token, never adapter class
- Module binding: `{ provide: 'PortName', useClass: AdapterClass }` in providers

### TypeScript
- `strict: true` always enabled
- FORBIDDEN: `any` type. Use `unknown` + type narrowing
- FORBIDDEN: `.then/.catch`. Always use `async/await`
- Explicit return types on all public methods
- File names: `kebab-case`. Classes: `PascalCase`. Variables: `camelCase`

### Security & Multi-tenancy
- Every business query MUST filter by `tenant_id`
- FORBIDDEN: storing tokens in localStorage
- FORBIDDEN: logging passwords, tokens, card data
- FORBIDDEN: storing full card numbers
- class-validator with `whitelist: true, forbidNonWhitelisted: true`
- Login error messages must be generic (never reveal if email exists)

### API & Data
- Never return Entity outside Service — always use DTO
- DTOs must use class-validator decorators
- Response format: `{ success, data, message?, meta?, error? }`
- Monetary values: `numeric(10, 2)` in Drizzle schema — FORBIDDEN: `float`, `real`, `integer` (cents)
- Drizzle returns `numeric` as `string` → convert with `parseFloat()` ONLY in Mapper
- Monetary arithmetic via `Money` value object — never raw math in services/controllers
- DTO validation for money fields: `@IsNumber({ maxDecimalPlaces: 2 }) @Min(0)`
- All business tables must have `tenant_id` column with index
- Controllers are thin: validate → delegate → return

### Testing
- Every new Service/Entity MUST have `.spec.ts`
- Unit tests mock Ports (never real adapters)
- Pattern: Arrange → Act → Assert
- Min coverage: 90% domain, 80% services, 75% general

## Module Structure
```
src/modules/{module}/
  domain/entities/          → Business entities with validation
  domain/value-objects/     → Immutable value objects
  domain/ports/input/       → Use case interfaces
  domain/ports/output/      → Repository/gateway interfaces
  application/services/     → Use case orchestration
  application/dtos/         → Input/Output DTOs with validation
  application/mappers/      → Entity ↔ DTO conversion
  infrastructure/controllers/ → HTTP endpoints (thin)
  infrastructure/repositories/ → Drizzle ORM implementations
  infrastructure/adapters/  → External service implementations
  {module}.module.ts        → NestJS module with Port→Adapter bindings
```

## Documentation
Read `docs/00-ai-system-prompt.md` first — it contains role definition, task routing (which doc to read for each task), constraints, fallback behavior, self-verification checklist, and common AI mistakes to avoid.

## Self-Check After Generating Code
- [ ] Domain doesn't import infrastructure?
- [ ] Ports are pure interfaces?
- [ ] Injected via string token?
- [ ] DTOs have class-validator decorators?
- [ ] Queries filter by tenant_id?
- [ ] Response is DTO (not Entity)?
- [ ] No `any` in generated code?
- [ ] Tests created for new logic?
- [ ] No sensitive data in responses?
